body_text.text:
To determine the optimal climatic conditions for the 2003 SARS epidemic in Beijing, a regression equation was derived using the most strongly correlated factors:Y=218.692−0.698Xt−2.043Xh+2.282Xwin which Y is the estimated number of SARS cases, and Xt, Xh, and Xw are the mean temperature, humidity, and wind velocity, respectively, on the selected day or a selected period during the SARS epidemic. The regression model was tested against rigorous case report data from the Beijing epidemic and found to fit well with the reported daily number of new SARS cases (r
2 = 0.847, mean = 58.5, SD = 40.4;
Table 1). The strongest associations were identified for the mean temperature and humidity recorded 13 to 17 days before the confirmation of SARS, and the mean wind speed 9 to 13 days before a clinical diagnosis of the disease.
